Here is the fixed unit test:

```java
package original;

import org.junit.Test;
import static org.junit.Assert.*;

public class CountDistinctCharactersTest {

    @Test
    public void testCountDistinctCharacters() {
        String string = "Hello World";
        int expected = 8;
        int actual = CountDistinctCharacters.countDistinctCharacters(string);
        assertEquals(expected, actual);
    }

    @Test
    public void testCountDistinctCharactersWithEmptyString() {
        String string = "";
        int expected = 0;
        int actual = CountDistinctCharacters.countDistinctCharacters(string);
        assertEquals(expected, actual);
    }

    @Test
    public void testCountDistinctCharactersWithNullString() {
        String string = null;
        int expected = 0;
        int actual = CountDistinctCharacters.countDistinctCharacters(string);
        assertEquals(expected, actual);
    }

    @Test
    public void testCountDistinctCharactersWithRepeatedCharacters() {
        String string = "Hello";
        int expected = 4;
        int actual = CountDistinctCharacters.countDistinctCharacters(string);
        assertEquals(expected, actual);
    }
}
```

The error in the unit test was caused by a `NullPointerException` in the `testCountDistinctCharactersWithNullString` test case. This occurred because the `countDistinctCharacters` method was not handling the case when the input string is `null`. To fix this, I have updated the `countDistinctCharacters` method to handle `null` strings by returning 0.
